     <font class="TallRed">Of fish and solitude<a name="108970582180166177">&nbsp;</a></font>
		<div class="blackjustified" style="background-color:#eeeeee;padding:5px 5px 5px 5px;border-top:3px solid #cccccc;border-bottom:1px solid #333333;border-left:1px solid #cccccc;border-right:1px solid #cccccc;">
          So I spent this weekend with some of my best friends, camping and fishing for two and a half epiphany-filled days on the grassy shores of Lake Anna. It was my first fishing trip ever, and I've discovered that I love the anti-sport--the discipline, devotion, and patience involved, and the inevitable mastery that can only come from these things over a lifetime of fishing. I would have never guessed that such wholesome fulfillment was but a rod, tackle, and lake away at all times. See, when I'm fishing, it's ok that people break plans with me and don't return my calls. It's ok that I've got a 6 hour drive back to the daily grind. It's ok that my car's a piece and I haven't the time nor drive to get it fixed or get a better one. It's ok that girls toy with me--because I'll toy right back. It doesn't even matter if I don't catch a thing...The point is I'm out fishing, and not worrying about these things. And this weekend was made even better by the fact that I was with a bunch of friends that I know I can absolutely trust and do place absolute trust. It was like shared solitude, away from all the madness of the real world.<br /><br />Good weekend fellas...good weekend...<br />
          <div class="byline">
<b>beelo</b>&nbsp;@ 3:17 AM [<a href="http://www.devlogik.com/www/E3R_2/blog/2004/07/of-fish-and-solitude.php" title="permanent link">#</a>|<a href="mailto:doctabeelo@yahoo.com?subject=RE: E3R POST #108970582180166177&body=Hey beelo!">e</a>]</div>
		</div><br>



